--- write a SQLite database with the SQLite output format ---
--- the produced file is a real SQLite database (read it with the sqlite3 CLI) ---
0|0|
1|1|1
2|2|
3|3|3
4|4|
--- read it back with the SQLite input format (round trip, including NULLs) ---
0	0	\N
1	1	1
2	2	\N
3	3	3
4	4	\N
--- read a database created directly by the sqlite3 CLI, selecting a table by name ---
cat	4
spider	8
--- a table name with a double quote is escaped and read correctly ---
hello
--- a structure with a wrong number of columns is rejected ---
INCORRECT_NUMBER_OF_COLUMNS
--- a SQLite text value equal to the null marker is not mistaken for SQL NULL ---
NULL	0
\N	1
--- SQL NULL in a non-nullable column with input_format_null_as_default = 0 is rejected ---
INCORRECT_DATA
--- SQL NULL in a non-nullable column with input_format_null_as_default = 1 becomes the default ---

NULL
--- SQL NULL with input_format_null_as_default = 1 honors the table DEFAULT expression ---
NULL
fallback
--- LowCardinality(Nullable) keeps SQL NULL and the textual null marker apart ---
NULL	0
\N	1
--- SQL NULL in a LowCardinality non-nullable column with input_format_null_as_default = 0 is rejected ---
INCORRECT_DATA
--- reading works with input_format_allow_seeks = 0 (the database is buffered in memory) ---
NULL	0
\N	1
--- a second insert into an existing SQLite file is rejected (the format does not support appends) ---
CANNOT_APPEND_TO_FILE
--- writing to a non-file is not supported ---
NOT_IMPLEMENTED
